ce:section.ce:para:
Electrode modification was completed in two steps. Firstly, C-dots coating onto the surface of PGE, followed by electro-synthesis of chiral selective MIP. Pretreatment of PGE, synthesis of C-dots and FSA are discussed in detailed in Supplementary Data Section S.1. Firstly, electro-deposition of PANI-FSA film on a PGE was carried out by cyclic voltammetry in 15mL containing 0.1mM aniline, 0.1mM FSA, and 0.1mM L-AA in 0.1mM H2SO4 and the pH was adjusted to 5.67. The cycling potential range was between –0.2 and 0.8V with a scan rate of 100mVs−1. The electro-deposition was finished after 50 cycles. After that, the three-electrode system was transferred into a 1% ammonium aqueous solution, and a negative potential of –0.4V was applied on the PANI-FSA electrode for 4000s (1.1hr) for the de-doping (extraction) of L-AA templates and formation of chiral sites (Scheme 1
                        ). The resulted MI-PANI-FSA-C-dots/PGE contains molecular cavity selective for L-AA (Electrode 1). The MI-PANI-FSA-C-dots/PGE containing molecular cavity selective for D-AA (Electrode 2) prepared under same operating parameter and experimental conditions. A different functional group in PANI-FSA could interact through non covalent interactions i.e. electrostatic attractions and hydrogen bonding with the substituted groups of the L-AA molecule (Scheme 2
                        ). These interactions presumably define the subsequent affinity and selectivity of the imprinted polymers towards L-AA in adduct. De-doping of L-AA by applying −0.4V, results in creation of chiral cavity commensurate with the molecular shape, size, and functionality of L-AA. Non-imprinted sensor (NI-PANI-FSA-C-dots/PGE) was prepared identically with the imprinted process but without addition of D-AA/L-AA. All the experimental conditions favorable for chiral sensor fabrication and electrochemical detection of D-AA/L-AA were optimized; for details vide Supplementary Data section S.1 and Fig. S1.
